    {
      "finding_id": "accounts_password_pam_minlen",
      "is_optimal": false,
      "approve": true,
      "feedback": "The plan will set the required minimum password length by adding a drop\u2011in file, which satisfies the vulnerability. It includes a backup of the drop\u2011in directory and removes duplicate entries, which is good. However, it does not back up the primary /etc/security/pwquality.conf file, does not handle the case where the .conf.d directory is empty or missing, and does not address any existing minlen settings that may reside in the main configuration file.",
      "concerns": [
        "Only the pwquality.conf.d directory is backed up; the main /etc/security/pwquality.conf is not, so changes to the primary config could be lost.",
        "The sed command will fail if no *.conf files exist in the directory, causing the script to stop.",
        "Existing minlen settings in the main configuration file are not removed or overridden explicitly, which could lead to duplicate definitions.",
        "Assumes the pwquality.conf.d directory exists on all target systems."
      ],
      "suggested_improvements": [
        "Create a backup of /etc/security/pwquality.conf in addition to the .conf.d directory.",
        "Add a check for the existence of the pwquality.conf.d directory and handle an empty glob safely (e.g., using a loop or nullglob).",
        "Consider removing or updating any minlen entry in the main /etc/security/pwquality.conf to avoid duplicates.",
        "After creating the new drop\u2011in file, verify that the effective minlen value is as expected (e.g., using pwscore or grep)."
